  "doi": "10.1073/pnas.1603106113",
  "title": "Molecular basis for universal HLA-A*0201-restricted CD8+ T-cell immunity against influenza viruses.",
  "journal": "Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America",
  "year": 2016,
  "authors": "Valkenburg SA, Josephs TM, Clemens EB, Grant EJ, Nguyen TH, Wang GC, Price DA, Miller A, Tong SY, Thomas PG, Doherty PC, Rossjohn J, Gras S, Kedzierska K."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examined CD8+ T-cell immunity in HLA-A*0201+ individuals responding to the conserved influenza M1 epitope (M158) and compared it to responses against the variable NP418 epitope presented by HLA-B*3501. A dominant public TCR (TRAV27/TRBV19+) was selected across HLA-A*0201+ donors and exhibited cross-recognition of naturally occurring M158 variants through induced-fit molecular mimicry, as revealed by ternary crystal structures of TCR-peptide-MHC complexes. This plasticity explains why the M158 epitope remains conserved across influenza strains and why HLA-A*0201+ individuals mount universal CTL responses despite viral evolution. The findings have broad implications for influenza vaccine design, indicating that inclusion of variant peptides could elicit broader cross-reactive immunity, particularly against epitopes that are underrepresented in naturally primed memory populations.",
